    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Problem\n\n`vim.fs` does not expose a way to ask if a path is a filesystem root (I needed this for a feature I'm working on and noticed it could also be used elsewhere in the codebase).\n\nContext: `vim.fs` sits at a rocky boundary between internal path semantics, vimscript-era helpers & libuv. My takeaway from recent issues is that path-semantics new additions to `vim.fs` need one simple, cross-platform, and _new_ behavior that isn't trivial to write a wrapper for (#27068, #37698, #31361) - a root predicate fits the bill.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nOne function in `vim.fs` handling linux + windows roots, as well as windows unc/device-roots like `//server/share`, `'//?/UNC/server/share'`, etc.\n\n### Alternatives Considered\n\n`vim.fs.dirname(path) == path`. However, this does not obviously cover all UNC/device-root cases that `vim.fs.normalize()` now models. Basically, all the logic below, for a truly cross-platform correct root detection, has to be double-checked.\n\n### Prospective Implementation\n\n```lua\n---@param path string\n---@return boolean\nlocal function isroot(path)\n  path = vim.fs.normalize(path)\n\n  -- Covers POSIX root and normal Windows drive roots handled by vim.fs.dirname().\n  if vim.fs.dirname(path) == path then\n    return true\n  end\n\n  -- Windows UNC share root: //server/share\n  if path:match('^//[^/]+/[^/]+/?$') then\n    return true\n  end\n\n  -- Windows device UNC share root: //?/UNC/server/share or //./UNC/server/share\n  if path:match('^//[?.]/UNC/[^/]+/[^/]+/?$') then\n    return true\n  end\n\n  return false\nend\n```",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
